<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="phenology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Flowering was observed in September and October. Fruiting was only observed in November, but probably extends till December.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jia X. Li" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gentianaceae" genus="Swertia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Swertia hongquanii" order="Gentianales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hongquanii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Swertia hongquanii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the type location in Tianmenshan National Forest Park. The climate here is cool, foggy and humid (annual rainfall ca. 1700 mm) and belongs to the subtropical monsoon climate (
<bibRefCitation author="Li, JX" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Tropical and Subtropical Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="573 - 576" refId="B13" refString="Li, JX, Luo, KW, Huang, HQ, Mou, C, 2008. Additions novelty to the seed plants flora of Tianmen Shan, Zhangjiajie, Hunan Province. Journal of Tropical and Subtropical Botany 16 (6): 573 - 576" title="Additions novelty to the seed plants flora of Tianmen Shan, Zhangjiajie, Hunan Province." volume="16" year="2008">Li et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0134895" author="Zhang, GJ" journalOrPublisher="Edinburgh Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B19" refString="Zhang, GJ, Hu, HH, Zhang, CF, Tian, XJ, Peng, H, Gao, TG, 2015. Inaccessible Biodiversity on Limestone Cliffs: Astertianmenshananensis (Asteraceae), a new critically endangered species from China. PLoS One 10(8): e0134895. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0134895" title="Inaccessible Biodiversity on Limestone Cliffs: Astertianmenshananensis (Asteraceae), a new critically endangered species from China. PLoS One 10 (8): e 0134895." url="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0134895" year="2015">Zhang et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
). The new species grows on the tops of steep limestone mountains surrounded by cliffs above an altitude of ca. 1400 m. The clifftops are covered by mixed evergreen-deciduous forest dominated by species of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Swertia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Gentianales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fagaceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lauraceae" genus="Swertia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Gentianales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Lauraceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Swertia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Gentianales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Betulaceae</taxonomicName>
